                                                <div class="text-center mb-3">
                                                    <h4 class="fw-bold mb-1 text-primary">What is DNS?</h4>
                                                    <p class="lead domain-lead">
                                                        Imagine you’re trying to visit your friend’s house, but instead of remembering the coordinates, you just remember their <b class="domain-term">name</b>. Easy, right? That’s exactly what <b class="domain-term">DNS</b> does for websites.
                                                        <br><br>
                                                        <b class="domain-term">DNS</b> stands for <b>Domain Name System</b>. When you type a website like <span class="domain-example">catsrock.com</span> into your browser, DNS looks up the real address (<span class="domain-example">IP address</span>) so your device knows where to go.
                                                        <br><br>
                                                        It’s like asking your phone, <span class="domain-quote">“Take me to Pizza Palace”</span>, and it magically knows the exact location.
                                                        <br><br>
                                                        When setting up <span class="domain-term">SSL certificates</span>, DNS is super important — you might be asked to add special records (like <span class="domain-txt">TXT</span> or <span class="domain-txt">CNAME</span>) to your domain’s DNS settings to prove you own the domain.
                                                        <br><br>
                                                        So yeah, <b class="domain-term">DNS</b> is kinda like your Internet matchmaker. It connects <b>names</b> to <b>addresses</b>.
                                                    </p>
