                                                <div class="text-center mb-3">
                                                    <h4 class="fw-bold mb-1">What is DNS01?</h4>

                                                    <p class="lead domain-lead">
                                                        <b class="domain-term">DNS-01</b> is a challenge type used by certificate authorities (like <span class="domain-vendor">Let’s Encrypt</span>) to verify that <b>you own the domain</b> you’re requesting an SSL certificate for.
                                                        <br><br>
                                                        Instead of clicking a link or uploading a file, the <b class="domain-term">DNS-01 challenge</b> asks you to add a special <b class="domain-txt">TXT record</b> to your domain’s DNS settings. This record contains a unique verification token that proves you control the domain.
                                                        <br><br>
                                                        Once the record is live, <span class="domain-vendor">Let’s Encrypt</span> (or another provider) checks your DNS zone, finds the token, and says: <span class="domain-quote">‘Yup, they own it!’</span> — then boom, you’re approved!
                                                        <br><br>
                                                        <b>When is DNS-01 useful?</b>
                                                        <ul class="domain-list">
                                                            <li>For domains with <b>no website yet</b> (no HTTP access).</li>
                                                            <li>For issuing <span class="domain-term">wildcard certificates</span> like <span class="domain-example">*.example.com</span>.</li>
                                                            <li>When automating SSL for many subdomains.</li>
                                                        </ul>
                                                    </p>


